 // Sort the array bubbleSort(numbers); System.out.println(\\"Sorted array: \\"); for(int num : numbers){ System.out.print(num + \\" \\"); } // Calculate median double median; if(numbers.length % 2 == 0){ median = ((double)numbersnumbers.length/2 + (double)numbersnumbers.length/2 - 1)/2; } else { median = (double) numbersnumbers.length/2; } System.out.println(\\"nMedian: \\" + median); } // Bubble sort implementation public static void bubbleSort(int arr){ int n = arr.length; boolean swapped; for(int i = 0; i < n-1; i++){ swapped = false; for(int j = 0; j < n-1-i; j++){ if(arrj > arrj+1){ int temp = arrj; arrj = arrj+1; arrj+1 = temp; swapped = true; } } // If no two elements were swapped in the inner loop, then the array is already sorted if(!swapped) break; } } } ``` In this program, we first sort the array using the bubble sort algorithm. Then we check if the length of the array is even or odd. If it\'s even, we take the average of the two middle numbers as the median. If it\'s odd, we simply take the middle number as the median. The output of this program would be: ``` Sorted array: 5 8 9 10 21 Median: 9.0 ```"},{"prompt":"In the allocation of budgets for business growth strategies, five different departments of a company have varying budget allocations. Each department has to allocate their budget to one of the following specific strategies: - Strategy A: Utilize data analytics tools - Strategy B: Implement customer relationship management software - Strategy C: Use digital marketing tactics - Strategy D: Explore e-commerce options - Strategy E: Develop a content marketing strategy. It is required that the department with the biggest budget must allocate their funds to Strategy D while the department with the smallest budget must allocate their funds to Strategy E. Moreover, the department with the second-largest budget is prohibited from choosing Strategy C. Can you determine the budget allocation and specific strategy choice for each department, considering t